    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-06-26T20:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-06-26T20:00:00-05:00" n="881"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d881">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">033.1161 Johnston, Eric/13: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-06-27T04:00:00+03:00"
                            >June 27, 1944—4 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received June 27—12:15 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2295. This evening<note n="77" xml:id="d881fn1">June 26.</note> I introduced Eric
                    Johnston to Marshal Stalin. The conversation, which lasted 2½ hours, was most
                    affable. Johnston was much impressed with Stalin’s intimate knowledge of
                    American production figures, both war and prewar. Stalin gave him considerable
                    information as to Soviet production and future objectives.</p>
                <p>Johnston indicated that he would do everything he could to promote extension of
                    credits by the United States to Russia for the purchase of American machinery
                    for reconstruction and assured the Marshal that American business desired the
                    development of the fullest trade and commerce with the Soviet Union in both
                    directions. A detailed report will follow.<note n="78" xml:id="d881fn2">See
                        telegram 2369, June 30, 3 p.m., from Moscow, <ref target="#pg_973">p.
                            973</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Johnston handled himself well and Stalin obviously liked him and what he
                    said.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harriman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
